User:

The starting point for accessing the website. Represents the end-user who interacts with the web application.
Domain Name System (DNS):

Converts the domain name www.foobar.com to an IP address (8.8.8.8). Essential for directing user requests to the correct server.
Server:

The central machine where all components are hosted. Necessary for housing the web server, application server, application files, and database.
Web Server (Nginx):

Manages incoming HTTP requests and serves static content. Forwards dynamic requests to the application server. Essential for efficient request handling and load distribution.
Application Server:

Processes application logic and interacts with the database. Necessary for executing the backend code and generating dynamic responses.
Application Files (Code Base):

Contains the actual code of the web application. Critical for defining the functionality and behavior of the application.
Database (MySQL):

Stores and manages application data. Required for data persistence and retrieval, ensuring the application can maintain and access its data.
Domain Name Configuration (foobar.com):

Configured with a www record pointing to the server's IP address (8.8.8.8). Ensures the domain name directs user requests to the correct server.
Each element plays a specific role in ensuring the website is accessible, functional, and efficient in handling user requests and data management.
